1
00:00:47,504 --> 00:00:52,601
11:55. Almost midnight.

2
00:00:52,642 --> 00:00:56,237
Enough time for one more story.

3
00:00:56,279 --> 00:01:01,273
One more story
before 12:00...

4
00:01:01,318 --> 00:01:03,752
just to keep us warm.

5
00:01:05,455 --> 00:01:11,724
In five minutes,
it will be the 21st of April.

6
00:01:11,762 --> 00:01:16,995
One hundred years ago,
on the 21st of April...

7
00:01:17,033 --> 00:01:20,935
out on the waters
around Spivey Point...

8
00:01:20,971 --> 00:01:25,704
a small clipper ship
drew toward land.

9
00:01:25,742 --> 00:01:30,441
Suddenly, out of the night,
the fog rolled in.

10
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:33,449
For a moment,
they could see nothing...

11
00:01:33,483 --> 00:01:35,951
not a foot ahead of them.

12
00:01:35,986 --> 00:01:39,683
Then they saw a light.

13
00:01:39,723 --> 00:01:45,184
By God, it was a fire
burning on the shore...

14
00:01:45,228 --> 00:01:49,756
strong enough to penetrate
the swirling mist.

15
00:01:49,800 --> 00:01:54,237
They steered a course
toward the light...

16
00:01:54,271 --> 00:01:58,469
but it was a campfire
like this one.

17
00:01:58,508 --> 00:02:02,911
The ship crashed
against the rocks.

18
00:02:02,946 --> 00:02:05,244
The hull sheared in two.

19
00:02:05,282 --> 00:02:08,251
The mast snapped like a twig...

20
00:02:08,285 --> 00:02:13,279
and the wreckage sank
with all the men aboard.

21
00:02:14,791 --> 00:02:16,918
At the bottom of the sea...

22
00:02:16,960 --> 00:02:20,760
lay the ''Elizabeth Dane''
with her crew...

23
00:02:20,797 --> 00:02:24,255
their lungs
filled with salt water...

24
00:02:24,301 --> 00:02:28,931
their eyes open
and staring into the darkness.

25
00:02:28,972 --> 00:02:32,931
And above,
as suddenly as it had come...

26
00:02:32,976 --> 00:02:34,773
the fog lifted...

27
00:02:34,811 --> 00:02:37,609
receded
back across the ocean...

28
00:02:37,647 --> 00:02:40,309
and never came again.

29
00:02:40,350 --> 00:02:43,615
But it is told
by the fishermen...

30
00:02:43,653 --> 00:02:46,622
and their fathers
and grandfathers...

31
00:02:46,656 --> 00:02:51,059
that when the fog returns
to Antonio Bay...

32
00:02:51,094 --> 00:02:55,053
the men
at the bottom of the sea...

33
00:02:55,098 --> 00:02:58,556
out in the water
by Spivey Point...

34
00:02:58,602 --> 00:03:03,471
will rise up
and search for the campfire...

35
00:03:03,507 --> 00:03:10,003
that led them
to their dark and icy death.

36
00:03:12,382 --> 00:03:18,287
Twelve o' clock,
the 21st of April.

37
00:04:12,776 --> 00:04:14,403
It's twelve midnight...

38
00:04:14,444 --> 00:04:16,810
and we just started
into the witching hour.

39
00:04:16,846 --> 00:04:20,213
This is Stevie Wayne,
on top of the world tonight.

40
00:04:20,250 --> 00:04:23,617
And I'll be here
right up until about 1:00.

41
00:04:50,847 --> 00:04:53,281
I'm all through, Father.

42
00:04:53,316 --> 00:04:56,012
Oh, thank you, Bennett.

43
00:04:56,052 --> 00:05:00,785
I won't need you
until four tomorrow, Bennett.

44
00:05:00,824 --> 00:05:02,155
Yes, sir.

45
00:05:03,460 --> 00:05:06,395
Would you like something to
keep you warm on the way home?

46
00:05:06,429 --> 00:05:09,398
No, thank you.
Father, can I get paid?

47
00:05:11,668 --> 00:05:17,470
Why don't you come in at six
instead of four tomorrow?

48
00:05:17,507 --> 00:05:19,668
Yes, sir.

49
00:05:29,919 --> 00:05:31,819
Bennett?

50
00:06:47,030 --> 00:06:48,759
It's 59 degrees outside.

51
00:06:48,798 --> 00:06:51,528
And let me be the first
to wish Antonio Bay...

52
00:06:51,568 --> 00:06:53,035
a happy birthday.

53
00:06:53,069 --> 00:06:56,596
We're one hundred years old
today.

54
00:06:56,639 --> 00:06:58,869
The weatherman's
been trying to spoil it for us.

55
00:06:58,908 --> 00:07:01,001
He says we may be
in for some rain tonight.

56
00:07:01,044 --> 00:07:05,242
But from where I'm sitting,
it looks like clear skies.

57
00:07:05,281 --> 00:07:08,079
I think the weatherman's
been working too hard.

58
00:07:08,118 --> 00:07:10,052
Well, I'll stay here
for another hour...

59
00:07:10,086 --> 00:07:12,384
just to see if he's right.

60
00:07:12,422 --> 00:07:14,947
And I'm inviting you
to stay here with me.

61
00:07:16,092 --> 00:07:20,256
There's a cutter run aground
over here on the east bay, over.

62
00:07:21,498 --> 00:07:25,730
Global 1X5.
It's the ''Lady Belle Pacific.''

63
00:07:25,769 --> 00:07:29,967
Serial number 024KL596. Over.

64
00:07:30,006 --> 00:07:32,406
Global 1X5,
the ''Lady Belle Pacific''...

65
00:07:32,442 --> 00:07:34,467
is seaworthy, no major damage.

66
00:07:34,511 --> 00:07:36,069
Why don't you
send a tow on over here...

67
00:07:36,112 --> 00:07:39,104
about a quarter mile
above the Boatel. Over.

68
00:11:36,219 --> 00:11:40,815
This is KAB,
Antonio Bay, California.

69
00:11:42,158 --> 00:11:45,184
Six minutes after midnight.

70
00:11:45,228 --> 00:11:46,456
Haven't heard
from the weatherman yet...

71
00:11:46,496 --> 00:11:48,964
so I can't say for sure
about that rain...

72
00:11:48,998 --> 00:11:53,094
but there's a full moon
and no clouds in the sky.

73
00:11:54,604 --> 00:11:56,094
I'm Stevie Wayne.

74
00:11:56,139 --> 00:11:58,573
And if you don't have anything
to do right now...

75
00:11:58,608 --> 00:12:02,601
I'll be here playing music
all through the witching hour.

76
00:12:06,482 --> 00:12:08,575
Even if you do
have something to do...

77
00:12:08,618 --> 00:12:10,745
keep me turned on for a while...

78
00:12:10,787 --> 00:12:13,585
and I'll try my best
to do the same for you.

79
00:12:13,623 --> 00:12:14,817
OK!

80
00:12:36,412 --> 00:12:38,937
-How far you going?
-Other side of town.

81
00:12:38,981 --> 00:12:40,312
That's close enough.

82
00:12:42,151 --> 00:12:44,984
-Make it?
-Yeah. Thank you.

83
00:12:55,431 --> 00:12:57,160
Sip?

84
00:12:57,200 --> 00:12:58,690
Thanks.

85
00:13:05,274 --> 00:13:08,334
Listen,
I never hitchhiked before.

86
00:13:08,377 --> 00:13:10,470
I just really want
to be careful.

87
00:13:10,513 --> 00:13:12,413
-Can I ask you something?
-Sure.

88
00:13:12,448 --> 00:13:14,939
Are you weird?

89
00:13:14,984 --> 00:13:17,145
Yes, I am.

90
00:13:17,186 --> 00:13:19,177
Yes, I am weird.

91
00:13:19,222 --> 00:13:21,747
You are weird.
Thank God you're weird.

92
00:13:21,791 --> 00:13:24,624
The last one was so normal,
it was disgusting.

93
00:13:24,660 --> 00:13:26,457
He picked me up
in Santa Barbara.

94
00:13:26,496 --> 00:13:28,657
By the time we got to Carmel
he wanted to marry me.

95
00:13:28,698 --> 00:13:31,360
Oh, yeah. I thought
you never hitchhiked before.

96
00:13:35,505 --> 00:13:37,496
Not before last week.

97
00:13:37,540 --> 00:13:40,407
You're my...

98
00:13:40,443 --> 00:13:42,001
thirteenth ride.

99
00:13:42,044 --> 00:13:44,774
Oh, great. Weird and unlucky.

100
00:13:44,814 --> 00:13:47,442
We'll see.

101
00:13:50,520 --> 00:13:51,714
Look out!

102
00:13:58,694 --> 00:13:59,956
-Are you all right?
-I'm fine.

103
00:13:59,996 --> 00:14:02,226
-You're sure?
-I think so.

104
00:14:02,265 --> 00:14:03,823
What the hell was--

105
00:14:10,306 --> 00:14:12,501
It's exactly twelve minutes
after midnight...

106
00:14:12,542 --> 00:14:14,407
and this is Stevie Wayne.

107
00:14:14,443 --> 00:14:16,274
Let's get out of here.

108
00:14:18,514 --> 00:14:21,347
I'm high tonight in the KAB
lighthouse on Spivey Point.

109
00:14:21,384 --> 00:14:23,909
And in case you've forgotten,
it's April 21st...

110
00:14:23,953 --> 00:14:26,183
and a happy birthday
for Antonio Bay.

111
00:14:26,222 --> 00:14:29,089
Now, there's a celebration
planned for tonight.

112
00:14:29,125 --> 00:14:32,925
So if you're so excited
about it you can't sleep...

113
00:14:32,962 --> 00:14:35,556
well, stay up with me...

114
00:14:35,598 --> 00:14:40,900
and I'll figure out some way
to keep you occupied.

115
00:14:40,937 --> 00:14:42,097
Or not.

116
00:14:47,710 --> 00:14:49,610
-KAB.
-Hi, sweetheart.

117
00:14:49,645 --> 00:14:51,806
Hi, Dan. What have you got?

118
00:14:51,847 --> 00:14:53,712
Well, I'm just calling
to see if you're lonely...

119
00:14:53,749 --> 00:14:54,977
if there's anything
I can do about it.

120
00:14:55,017 --> 00:14:56,746
Never lonely, Dan.

121
00:14:56,786 --> 00:14:58,048
I thought
you were off work at 8:00.

122
00:14:58,087 --> 00:15:00,487
I changed shifts to make it
to the big party tonight.

123
00:15:00,523 --> 00:15:01,649
Will you be there?

124
00:15:01,691 --> 00:15:05,149
Until I can talk someone else...

125
00:15:05,194 --> 00:15:08,425
into giving up city life
for Antonio Bay, I'm it.

126
00:15:08,464 --> 00:15:11,433
-And ''it'' means day and night.
-Too much work.

127
00:15:11,467 --> 00:15:13,435
That's what I get
for owning a station.

128
00:15:13,469 --> 00:15:14,561
And if you don't tell me
why you called...

129
00:15:14,604 --> 00:15:16,902
in about fifteen seconds,
I'll have to hang up on you.

130
00:15:16,939 --> 00:15:19,407
-Want something to talk about?
-Anything.

131
00:15:19,442 --> 00:15:21,842
I've got a position
on a trawler about...

132
00:15:21,877 --> 00:15:25,540
fifteen miles out
called the ''Sea Grass.''

133
00:15:25,581 --> 00:15:27,139
And I've got
something on my scope--

134
00:15:27,183 --> 00:15:29,083
appears to be a fog bank.

135
00:15:29,118 --> 00:15:32,451
It's about 25 miles out,
moving in their direction.

136
00:15:32,488 --> 00:15:36,219
Thanks, Dan.
That's worth about ten seconds.

137
00:15:36,259 --> 00:15:38,284
I'm on the air. Bye.

138
00:15:43,099 --> 00:15:44,623
Ahoy, maties.

139
00:15:44,667 --> 00:15:47,534
This is KAB, Antonio Bay.

140
00:15:47,570 --> 00:15:51,438
Stevie Wayne here
beaming a signal across the sea.

141
00:15:51,474 --> 00:15:54,705
To the men of the ''Sea Grass,''
fifteen miles out tonight...

142
00:15:54,744 --> 00:15:56,109
a warm hello...

143
00:15:56,145 --> 00:15:58,875
and keep a watch out
for that fog bank...

144
00:15:58,914 --> 00:16:00,711
heading in from the east.

145
00:16:00,750 --> 00:16:02,217
Now, in the meantime...

146
00:16:02,251 --> 00:16:04,879
relax with me
while I play this song...

147
00:16:04,920 --> 00:16:08,549
from the Coupe DeVilles,
dedicated just to you.

148
00:16:08,591 --> 00:16:11,287
Boy, would I like to meet her.

149
00:16:11,327 --> 00:16:12,555
I saw her
at a grocery store one day.

150
00:16:12,595 --> 00:16:14,563
-And?
-You would like to meet her.

151
00:16:14,597 --> 00:16:17,566
She's crazy.
There's no fog bank out there.

152
00:16:17,600 --> 00:16:19,067
What do you know about her?

153
00:16:19,101 --> 00:16:21,433
-She owns that lighthouse.
-I know that.

154
00:16:21,470 --> 00:16:23,233
Her son plays Little League
with my kid brother.

155
00:16:23,272 --> 00:16:24,569
She's a mother?

156
00:16:24,607 --> 00:16:26,234
I thought
you were happily married.

157
00:16:26,275 --> 00:16:27,902
Not that happy.

158
00:16:27,943 --> 00:16:30,741
No fog bank out there.

159
00:16:38,321 --> 00:16:40,289
There's a fog bank out there.

160
00:16:42,124 --> 00:16:45,150
All right. I'm drunk enough.

161
00:16:45,194 --> 00:16:47,128
Let's go back.

162
00:16:47,163 --> 00:16:48,994
All right, all right.

163
00:16:53,169 --> 00:16:55,660
Al, come here.

164
00:16:55,705 --> 00:16:58,003
-Just give him a hand.
-Come here.

165
00:17:10,252 --> 00:17:12,345
What was that?

166
00:17:40,049 --> 00:17:42,108
Come here.

167
00:17:44,620 --> 00:17:46,611
What was that?

168
00:17:55,231 --> 00:17:56,892
It's the generator.

169
00:17:58,234 --> 00:18:00,327
Wha--wha...

170
00:18:04,440 --> 00:18:05,702
Al.

171
00:18:22,091 --> 00:18:23,649
It's gone.

172
00:18:23,692 --> 00:18:25,557
There was just a ship out there.

173
00:18:25,594 --> 00:18:27,221
Al, listen.

174
00:18:27,263 --> 00:18:29,390
Nothing.

175
00:18:29,432 --> 00:18:31,593
-Listen.
-Who's there?

176
00:18:42,778 --> 00:18:44,837
Who is that?

177
00:19:33,696 --> 00:19:35,425
Al, it's right beside us.

178
00:19:38,367 --> 00:19:42,098
It's big, Al. It's a ship.

179
00:19:42,137 --> 00:19:43,900
It's a big ship!

180
00:19:47,610 --> 00:19:49,407
What happened?
Did you get wet?

181
00:20:08,631 --> 00:20:11,429
It's 12:43...

182
00:20:11,467 --> 00:20:13,833
and I've got
four in a row for you...

183
00:20:13,869 --> 00:20:16,133
right here on KAB.

184
00:20:52,741 --> 00:20:55,107
Nothing but water, Stevie.

185
00:20:57,980 --> 00:21:00,107
But it sure beats Chicago.

186
00:21:05,621 --> 00:21:06,918
KAB.

187
00:21:06,956 --> 00:21:08,651
I like what you said...

188
00:21:08,691 --> 00:21:10,989
but for your information,
you lied.

189
00:21:11,026 --> 00:21:13,392
The fog bank
has moved due west...

190
00:21:13,429 --> 00:21:17,058
and probably
missed the ship entirely.

191
00:21:17,099 --> 00:21:18,930
Well, my gauges must be wrong.

192
00:21:18,968 --> 00:21:20,663
I've got a wind blowing
due east.

193
00:21:20,703 --> 00:21:23,263
What kind of a fog
blows against the wind?

194
00:21:23,305 --> 00:21:25,773
-You got me.
-I'm not so sure I want you.

195
00:21:25,808 --> 00:21:27,605
You're just
a voice on the phone.

196
00:21:27,643 --> 00:21:30,942
You're a voice on the radio.
We'd make a perfect couple.

197
00:21:32,948 --> 00:21:35,974
You let me take you to dinner
tonight, I'll prove it to you.

198
00:21:36,018 --> 00:21:37,918
Sorry, Dan.

199
00:21:37,953 --> 00:21:41,184
My idea of perfection
is a voice on the phone.

200
00:21:41,223 --> 00:21:43,919
OK, mystery lady.

201
00:21:43,959 --> 00:21:46,359
-Good night.
-Good night.

202
00:22:07,282 --> 00:22:08,442
Not bad.

203
00:22:10,219 --> 00:22:12,744
I started a week ago
in San Diego...

204
00:22:12,788 --> 00:22:16,189
right up the coast,
five drawings a day.

205
00:22:16,225 --> 00:22:18,022
It'll probably take me a month
to get to Vancouver...

206
00:22:18,060 --> 00:22:19,618
and if I can sell them
for five bucks apiece...

207
00:22:19,662 --> 00:22:21,960
-I'll be rich.
-Yeah.

208
00:22:24,833 --> 00:22:26,767
-Can I ask you something?
-Sure.

209
00:22:26,802 --> 00:22:28,827
What's your name?

210
00:22:28,871 --> 00:22:31,533
-Elizabeth.
-Nick.

211
00:22:31,573 --> 00:22:34,303
-Hello, Nick.
-Hi.

212
00:22:36,078 --> 00:22:38,171
Is that where you're from,
San Diego?

213
00:22:38,213 --> 00:22:40,613
Wait a minute. You said,
''Can I ask something?''

214
00:22:40,649 --> 00:22:42,844
Well, something,
to me, means one thing.

215
00:22:42,885 --> 00:22:45,547
-San Diego is two things.
-OK.

216
00:22:47,322 --> 00:22:52,282
Pasadena, and a lot of money.

217
00:22:52,327 --> 00:22:54,761
Never a chance to do
anything I want to do.

218
00:22:59,435 --> 00:23:01,630
What do you want to do?

219
00:23:01,670 --> 00:23:04,764
I don't know.

220
00:23:04,807 --> 00:23:08,004
That's OK. Me, neither.

221
00:23:08,043 --> 00:23:10,773
I think I got to have this one.
Can I buy it?

222
00:23:12,548 --> 00:23:14,106
The drawing's free.

223
00:24:11,340 --> 00:24:13,638
It's 1:00, straight up...

224
00:24:13,675 --> 00:24:17,270
the end of the witching hour,
and time for me to sign off.

225
00:24:23,585 --> 00:24:26,247
So until tomorrow night,
at 6 P.M...

226
00:24:26,288 --> 00:24:28,415
when KAB
comes back on the air...

227
00:24:28,457 --> 00:24:31,221
this is Stevie Wayne,
your night light...

228
00:24:31,260 --> 00:24:34,161
hoping you have
a nice rest of the night.

229
00:26:32,447 --> 00:26:34,176
Hey, Mom !

230
00:26:39,421 --> 00:26:42,447
Mom, come on. Get up.
Look what I found.

231
00:26:42,491 --> 00:26:47,121
Andy...I love you...

232
00:26:47,162 --> 00:26:49,596
but sometimes
you're a real pain.

233
00:26:49,631 --> 00:26:51,258
Sure, Mom, but look it.

234
00:26:51,300 --> 00:26:52,631
First, it was a gold coin.

235
00:26:52,668 --> 00:26:55,432
Then it turned into
this neat piece of wood.

236
00:26:55,470 --> 00:26:57,028
This is one of those times.

237
00:26:57,072 --> 00:26:58,767
Look at it, Mom.

238
00:27:02,978 --> 00:27:04,946
Good morning, Andrew.

239
00:27:04,980 --> 00:27:07,073
Did you have a nice time
last night?

240
00:27:07,115 --> 00:27:10,107
Yeah. Old Mr. Machen
told us ghost stories.

241
00:27:10,152 --> 00:27:12,882
Did you thank Mrs. Kobritz
for bringing you home?

242
00:27:12,921 --> 00:27:16,220
Yes, ma'am. Mom, can I have
a stomach pounder and a Coke?

243
00:27:16,258 --> 00:27:19,659
-After lunch.
-OK.

244
00:27:19,695 --> 00:27:21,390
I'm gonna go look
for another one.

245
00:27:21,430 --> 00:27:23,921
Maybe this time
I can get the gold coin.

246
00:27:48,724 --> 00:27:50,487
Where the hell is he?

247
00:27:50,525 --> 00:27:52,652
Rolled out of here
at 4:15 yesterday.

248
00:27:52,694 --> 00:27:55,060
-That's the last I saw of him.
-Al said 7:30, right here.

249
00:27:55,097 --> 00:27:57,190
You know Al.
If I were you--

250
00:27:57,232 --> 00:27:58,722
Did you call
the Coast Guard, Hank?

251
00:27:58,767 --> 00:28:00,792
Nick, they probably
got drunk last night.

252
00:28:00,836 --> 00:28:03,703
-No, he wouldn't do that.
-He'd do anything.

253
00:28:03,739 --> 00:28:06,003
Al and I got drunk so many times
I can't count them all...

254
00:28:06,041 --> 00:28:09,340
but we never got so shitfaced
we couldn't make it back in.

255
00:28:09,378 --> 00:28:11,369
He's too good a sailor
to stay out there all night...

256
00:28:11,413 --> 00:28:12,710
and not let somebody know.

257
00:28:12,748 --> 00:28:15,581
-You sound like his wife.
-Just his friend.

258
00:28:15,617 --> 00:28:17,414
-You worry too much, Nick.
-Yeah.

259
00:28:20,155 --> 00:28:21,884
Where are we going?

260
00:28:21,923 --> 00:28:24,892
I'm going to talk Ashcroft
into taking out his boat...

261
00:28:24,926 --> 00:28:26,484
and looking for the ''Sea Grass.''

262
00:28:26,528 --> 00:28:27,995
Who's Ashcroft?

263
00:28:28,030 --> 00:28:29,998
Someone who owes me a favor.

264
00:28:30,032 --> 00:28:32,000
Can I come along?

265
00:28:32,034 --> 00:28:34,502
I thought you had to move on
to Vancouver?

266
00:28:34,536 --> 00:28:35,764
Eventually.

267
00:28:42,944 --> 00:28:45,208
The sheriff
will drive his own car.

268
00:28:45,247 --> 00:28:48,045
The mayor and his wife
are to be picked up at 6:45...

269
00:28:48,083 --> 00:28:50,074
and brought to the mayor's box.

270
00:28:50,118 --> 00:28:52,609
Then we will have speeches
by the mayor...

271
00:28:52,654 --> 00:28:54,519
the sheriff, and me.

272
00:28:54,556 --> 00:28:56,854
-Do you have my notes?
-Yes, ma'am.

273
00:28:56,892 --> 00:28:58,689
Then we will pass out
the candles...

274
00:28:58,727 --> 00:29:00,490
and begin the procession.

275
00:29:00,529 --> 00:29:03,430
Then I will go home
and pass out.

276
00:29:03,465 --> 00:29:05,660
I'm almost afraid to look.

277
00:29:05,700 --> 00:29:06,962
Well...

278
00:29:09,871 --> 00:29:11,839
Not bad. Not bad at all.

279
00:29:11,873 --> 00:29:13,704
A work of art.

280
00:29:13,742 --> 00:29:16,870
Sandy, just be civil to me
for another five hours.

281
00:29:16,912 --> 00:29:18,504
That's all I ask.

282
00:29:18,547 --> 00:29:20,014
Let's see now.

283
00:29:20,048 --> 00:29:21,845
The candles.
Did you order the candles?

284
00:29:21,883 --> 00:29:23,612
What a thought--a candlelight
procession with no candles.

285
00:29:23,652 --> 00:29:25,916
All taken care of.

286
00:29:25,954 --> 00:29:28,218
And the promotional material--
did you get that to Stevie?

287
00:29:28,256 --> 00:29:30,690
Signed, sealed, and delivered.

288
00:29:30,725 --> 00:29:33,489
Sandy, you can be a very
annoying person at times...

289
00:29:33,528 --> 00:29:34,893
but you do keep me together.

290
00:29:34,930 --> 00:29:36,921
Thank you, Mrs. Williams.

291
00:30:05,961 --> 00:30:10,057
...Spivey Point.
As of 1:57 today...

292
00:30:10,098 --> 00:30:11,998
the ''Sea Grass''
had not responded...

293
00:30:12,033 --> 00:30:13,933
to radio communication.

294
00:30:13,969 --> 00:30:15,994
The Coast Guard
has begun a sweep...

295
00:30:16,037 --> 00:30:17,732
south from Watley...

296
00:30:17,772 --> 00:30:19,399
around Arcom Reef...

297
00:30:19,441 --> 00:30:21,602
and should be
in the area of Spivey Point...

298
00:30:21,643 --> 00:30:24,111
in approximately one hour.

299
00:30:24,146 --> 00:30:27,445
Repeating this bulletin
from the Coast Guard...

300
00:30:27,482 --> 00:30:29,450
be on the look out
for the ''Sea Grass''...

301
00:30:29,484 --> 00:30:31,281
a thirty-foot trawler...

302
00:30:31,319 --> 00:30:35,756
last seen approximately 15 miles
east of Spivey Point.

303
00:30:35,790 --> 00:30:37,781
If you sight this vessel...

304
00:30:37,826 --> 00:30:40,522
please notify
the Coast Guard immediately.

305
00:30:51,706 --> 00:30:55,642
Nick, can I ask you a question?

306
00:30:55,677 --> 00:30:57,076
Is it always like this?

307
00:30:57,112 --> 00:31:00,081
It's always different.

308
00:31:00,115 --> 00:31:02,140
You're worried, aren't you?

309
00:31:02,184 --> 00:31:05,551
Yeah. She can get real mean.

310
00:31:05,587 --> 00:31:06,952
There.

311
00:31:18,233 --> 00:31:21,168
If I can just get through
the speeches without yawning.

312
00:31:21,203 --> 00:31:23,467
-I couldn't sleep last night.
-Too excited?

313
00:31:23,505 --> 00:31:25,996
No. Al went out on his boat
last night and didn't come home.

314
00:31:26,041 --> 00:31:28,601
-He still isn't back.
-Mrs. Williams!

315
00:31:28,643 --> 00:31:30,076
I called the Coast Guard,
and they said...

316
00:31:30,111 --> 00:31:32,238
''Oh, he might have had
engine trouble.''

317
00:31:32,280 --> 00:31:34,441
They said not to worry.

318
00:31:34,482 --> 00:31:36,109
He was complaining
about his boat last week.

319
00:31:36,151 --> 00:31:37,618
Maybe you ought to go home.

320
00:31:37,652 --> 00:31:40,143
That's the last place
I want to go.

321
00:31:40,188 --> 00:31:42,122
My dog started to bark
at 12:00 last night...

322
00:31:42,157 --> 00:31:44,125
and didn't stop
until 6:00 this morning.

323
00:31:44,159 --> 00:31:45,421
What happened?

324
00:31:45,460 --> 00:31:47,587
He was pointed toward the ocean
and growling.

325
00:31:47,629 --> 00:31:48,789
What does that tell you?

326
00:31:48,830 --> 00:31:51,230
My dog goes crazy and
decides to bark at the water.

327
00:31:51,266 --> 00:31:53,234
I heard the church bells
at midnight...

328
00:31:53,268 --> 00:31:55,065
as I started
to drift off to sleep...

329
00:31:55,103 --> 00:31:57,799
and my car alarm went off
for absolutely no reason.

330
00:31:57,839 --> 00:32:00,399
-Really?
-Woke up the whole block.

331
00:32:00,442 --> 00:32:03,138
This town sits around for
100 years and nothing happens...

332
00:32:03,178 --> 00:32:05,510
and then one night,
the whole place falls apart.

333
00:32:08,083 --> 00:32:10,813
Take this line, too.

334
00:32:10,852 --> 00:32:14,447
Al! Tommy! Dick!

335
00:32:19,127 --> 00:32:21,652
Cabin and steering house
are empty.

336
00:32:21,696 --> 00:32:23,960
Maybe somebody picked them up.

337
00:32:25,634 --> 00:32:27,431
There's water in the generator.

338
00:32:27,469 --> 00:32:29,630
But the deck is dry as a bone.

339
00:32:55,897 --> 00:32:58,024
There you have it.
My next project...

340
00:32:58,066 --> 00:33:00,899
restoration of
the Morgantown Road Cemetery.

341
00:33:00,935 --> 00:33:03,165
It's historical.
Our ancestors are buried here.

342
00:33:03,204 --> 00:33:05,900
-It'll cost a lot.
-Come on. So?

343
00:33:05,940 --> 00:33:07,737
This town should be proud
of its past.

344
00:33:07,776 --> 00:33:09,368
But trying to get
anyone involved...

345
00:33:09,411 --> 00:33:11,845
in community affairs
is like pulling teeth.

346
00:33:11,880 --> 00:33:13,074
Better get
the estimates ready...

347
00:33:13,114 --> 00:33:14,581
for the council meeting
next month.

348
00:33:14,616 --> 00:33:15,742
Yes, ma'am.

349
00:33:15,784 --> 00:33:17,251
Sandy, you're
the only person I know...

350
00:33:17,285 --> 00:33:19,583
who can make ''Yes, ma'am''
sound like ''Screw you.''

351
00:33:19,621 --> 00:33:20,883
Yes, ma'am.

352
00:33:20,922 --> 00:33:22,048
Now, if we'll just say
a little prayer...

353
00:33:22,090 --> 00:33:24,115
asking that
he not be in his cups.

354
00:33:30,565 --> 00:33:32,294
Not a good sign.

355
00:33:34,936 --> 00:33:37,530
Father Malone?

356
00:33:45,513 --> 00:33:47,811
Another bad sign.

357
00:33:47,849 --> 00:33:50,579
You try the study,
and I'll look up front.

358
00:34:14,676 --> 00:34:18,407
-Jesus!
-I'm sorry, Mrs. Williams.

359
00:34:18,446 --> 00:34:21,142
-Mrs. Williams--
-Are you all right?

360
00:34:21,182 --> 00:34:23,275
I have something to show you.

361
00:34:28,823 --> 00:34:31,291
''December 9.

362
00:34:31,326 --> 00:34:35,228
''Met with Blake this evening
for the first time.

363
00:34:35,263 --> 00:34:36,890
''He stood in the shadows...

364
00:34:36,931 --> 00:34:40,731
''to prevent me from getting
a clear look at his face.

365
00:34:40,769 --> 00:34:44,364
''What a vile disease this is.

366
00:34:44,406 --> 00:34:48,365
''He is a rich man
with a cursed condition...

367
00:34:48,410 --> 00:34:49,934
''but this does not
prevent him...

368
00:34:49,978 --> 00:34:52,037
''from trying to better
his situation...

369
00:34:52,080 --> 00:34:54,412
''and that of his comrades
at the colony.''

370
00:35:15,136 --> 00:35:17,661
Every single gauge is broken.

371
00:35:20,041 --> 00:35:22,566
-All the glass is shattered.
-Remind you of something?

372
00:35:22,610 --> 00:35:24,601
-Last night.
-Your truck.

373
00:35:32,754 --> 00:35:34,779
Thermometer's broken.

374
00:35:36,724 --> 00:35:39,284
The mercury's stuck
at twenty degrees.

375
00:35:40,762 --> 00:35:46,564
No water got in here,
but something awful cold did.

376
00:35:46,601 --> 00:35:50,731
''December 11.
Blake's proposition is simple.

377
00:35:50,772 --> 00:35:53,206
''He wants to move off
Tanzier Island...

378
00:35:53,241 --> 00:35:57,905
''and relocate the entire colony
just north of here.

379
00:35:57,946 --> 00:35:59,937
''He has purchased
a clipper ship...

380
00:35:59,981 --> 00:36:05,476
''called the 'Elizabeth Dane.'
with part of his fortune....

381
00:36:05,520 --> 00:36:09,320
''and asks only for permission
to settle here.

382
00:36:09,357 --> 00:36:12,554
''I must balance my feelings
of mercy and compassion...

383
00:36:12,594 --> 00:36:14,653
''toward this poor man...

384
00:36:14,696 --> 00:36:17,221
''with my revulsion
at the thought...

385
00:36:17,265 --> 00:36:20,701
''of a leper colony
only a mile distant.''

386
00:36:38,720 --> 00:36:40,915
It's rusted to the wall.

387
00:36:44,392 --> 00:36:45,825
It was on.

388
00:36:53,735 --> 00:36:55,703
They drank a lot of beer
last night.

389
00:36:55,737 --> 00:36:57,364
Every night.

390
00:36:57,405 --> 00:36:59,703
What's it like?

391
00:36:59,741 --> 00:37:02,710
It's always the same.
Room starts spinning--

392
00:37:02,744 --> 00:37:03,938
I mean fishing.

393
00:37:07,348 --> 00:37:08,542
You fish.

394
00:37:08,583 --> 00:37:10,210
The only thing I know
about fishing...

395
00:37:10,251 --> 00:37:11,582
is you use a lot of worms.

396
00:37:13,688 --> 00:37:15,053
Salt water.

397
00:37:17,358 --> 00:37:19,883
She was clean two nights ago.
I checked her out myself.

398
00:37:19,928 --> 00:37:23,261
Now it's as if she's been
turned over in the water.

399
00:37:25,433 --> 00:37:29,529
''April 20.
The six of us met tonight.

400
00:37:29,571 --> 00:37:31,539
''From midnight until 1:00...

401
00:37:31,573 --> 00:37:35,031
''we planned the death
of Blake and his comrades.

402
00:37:35,076 --> 00:37:37,738
''I tell myself
that Blake's gold...

403
00:37:37,779 --> 00:37:39,747
''will allow
the church to be built...

404
00:37:39,781 --> 00:37:42,477
''and our small settlement
to become a township...

405
00:37:42,517 --> 00:37:45,748
''but it does not soothe
the horror that I feel...

406
00:37:45,787 --> 00:37:49,450
''being an accomplice to murder.''

407
00:37:54,162 --> 00:37:55,959
Now what?

408
00:37:55,997 --> 00:37:58,056
Wait for the Coast Guard.

409
00:38:02,904 --> 00:38:04,895
I'm sorry.

410
00:38:04,939 --> 00:38:06,201
What for?

411
00:38:06,240 --> 00:38:09,232
Ever since you picked me up,
things have been going wrong.

412
00:38:09,277 --> 00:38:11,336
The clock broke, the windows
have been breaking...

413
00:38:11,379 --> 00:38:12,937
the weirdo at the door
last night.

414
00:38:12,981 --> 00:38:16,212
-That isn't you.
-I'm not so sure.

415
00:38:16,250 --> 00:38:19,048
Things seem to happen to me.

416
00:38:19,087 --> 00:38:20,418
I'm bad luck.

417
00:38:21,990 --> 00:38:26,620
I don't believe in luck,
good or bad.

418
00:38:26,661 --> 00:38:28,925
I don't believe
in anything much...

419
00:38:31,399 --> 00:38:33,924
Something did happen once.

420
00:38:36,270 --> 00:38:38,738
My father was a fisherman.

421
00:38:38,773 --> 00:38:43,233
He ran a trawler
out of Whitely Reef.

422
00:38:43,277 --> 00:38:47,611
One night, late,
he was coming back in.

423
00:38:47,649 --> 00:38:51,676
He was out beyond the reef,
out near Spivey Point.

424
00:38:51,719 --> 00:38:54,415
He looked to windward...

425
00:38:54,455 --> 00:38:57,947
and saw a brig
under shortsail...

426
00:38:57,992 --> 00:39:00,222
heading right for him.

427
00:39:02,730 --> 00:39:06,723
And he radioed.
There was no reply.

428
00:39:06,768 --> 00:39:11,364
Nothing moved on the deck,
but she held her course.

429
00:39:12,573 --> 00:39:15,736
My dad and two of his hands
boarded the brig--

430
00:39:15,777 --> 00:39:18,439
the ''Resa Jane.''

431
00:39:18,479 --> 00:39:21,880
No one was on board.

432
00:39:21,916 --> 00:39:23,884
There was food on the table...

433
00:39:23,918 --> 00:39:26,216
and a hot, steaming
cup of coffee.

434
00:39:26,254 --> 00:39:30,884
But underneath, the tin cup
was rusted to the table.

435
00:39:30,925 --> 00:39:34,326
And then something caught
my father's eye.

436
00:39:34,362 --> 00:39:40,858
It was a gold doubloon
minted in Spain, 1867.

437
00:39:40,902 --> 00:39:43,564
My dad picked up the coin,
put it in his breast pocket...

438
00:39:43,604 --> 00:39:45,902
of his jacket,
and zippered it up.

439
00:39:45,940 --> 00:39:49,740
He came home,
told us the story.

440
00:39:49,777 --> 00:39:54,373
And he unzippered the pocket
to give me the coin.

441
00:39:54,415 --> 00:39:55,939
It was gone.

442
00:39:58,286 --> 00:40:00,277
I think I'll go
to Vancouver now.

443
00:40:06,627 --> 00:40:10,393
''April 21st. The deed is done.

444
00:40:10,431 --> 00:40:13,093
''Blake followed
our false fire on shore...

445
00:40:13,134 --> 00:40:16,934
''and his ship broke apart
on the rocks off Spivey Point.

446
00:40:16,971 --> 00:40:19,531
''We were aided
by an unearthly fog...

447
00:40:19,574 --> 00:40:22,270
''that rolled in
as if heaven-sent...

448
00:40:22,310 --> 00:40:26,110
''although God had no part
in our actions tonight.

449
00:40:26,147 --> 00:40:28,445
''Blake's gold
will be recovered tomorrow...

450
00:40:28,483 --> 00:40:33,045
''but may the Lord forgive us
for what we have done.''

451
00:40:33,087 --> 00:40:35,988
I couldn't read any further.

452
00:40:37,325 --> 00:40:41,193
Your grandfather
had a way with words.

453
00:40:43,364 --> 00:40:46,959
Our celebration tonight
is a travesty.

454
00:40:47,001 --> 00:40:49,663
We're honoring murderers.

455
00:41:39,821 --> 00:41:43,279
Side one,
KAB promos and lead-ins.

456
00:41:43,324 --> 00:41:48,193
More music on
top of the world KAB 1340.

457
00:41:49,630 --> 00:41:51,928
Thirty-three.

458
